## Overview

Built as part of the Advanced AI module at Newcastle University, this project combines two challenging deep learning pipelines: **food image segmentation** and **multimodal idiom grounding**.

## Part 1: Food Segmentation Pipeline

### The Challenge

Food image segmentation is hard — ingredients overlap, lighting varies, and 100+ classes share visual similarities. The published baseline on **FoodSeg103** (104 ingredient classes) was an FPN-ResNet50 architecture.

### My Approach: Progressive Architecture Upgrades

I designed a **3-stage progressive pipeline**, with each upgrade delivering measurable gains:

1. **U-Net (baseline)** — Established the segmentation pipeline end-to-end
2. **DeepLabV3+ with ASPP** — Added multi-scale context capture for better boundaries
3. **SegFormer-B2 Vision Transformer** — Captured long-range ingredient co-occurrence patterns that CNN architectures fundamentally cannot

### Result

The final SegFormer ViT model **surpassed the published FPN-ResNet50 academic baseline** on FoodSeg103.

## Part 2: Multimodal Idiomaticity Pipeline

### The Challenge

Idioms ("piece of cake", "spilled the beans") are hard for AI because their meaning isn't literal. Given an idiom and 5 candidate images, can a model rank which image best represents the idiomatic meaning?

### My 4-Stage Approach

1. **Gemini LLM Augmentation** — Tripled training diversity by generating semantically varied descriptions
2. **Zero-Shot CLIP Baseline** — Established what a pre-trained model could do without fine-tuning
3. **Fine-Tuned Sentence-Transformer Ranking Model** — The core of the system
4. **Evaluation Pipeline** — Custom ranking metrics

### Result

**85.2% test accuracy** — more than **2.5x the random baseline**.

